    {
      "avalancheActivity": {
        "comment": "The avalanche risk is considerable above the tree line in the morning and increases to high during the daytime changes, below it it is moderate. The main problem is wind slab avalanches. Slab avalanches can easily be triggered by individual winter sports enthusiasts or detach themselves. Avalanche prone locations are adjacent to ridgelines and distant from ridgelines on steep slopes of all aspects, behind slope discontinuities and in gullies and bowls, as well as in forest aisles and clearings. They increase in number and size with altitude. Above 1800 m, avalanches on very steep shady slopes can also tear through to deeper weak layers in the old snowpack and become large, especially in the afternoon with the renewed snowfall. Cracks when stepping on the snowpack and booming noises indicate the danger.\n\nSmall to medium-sized, spontaneous loose snow avalanches are possible from the steep terrain interspersed with rocks. Individual gliding avalanches are also possible.",
        "highlights": "The drifting snow situation is still tricky."
      },
